# n8n Node Basic Field Types Standards

1. Toggle Fields
   ```typescript
   // Clear toggle usage
   {
     displayName: 'Simplify Output',  // Clear what happens when false
     name: 'simplifyOutput',
     type: 'boolean',
     default: true,
     description: 'Whether to return a simplified version of the response',
   },

   // When toggle isn't clear enough, use options instead
   {
     displayName: 'Append Mode',      // Unclear what happens when false
     name: 'appendMode',
     type: 'options',
     options: [
       {
         name: 'Append to Existing',
         value: 'append',
       },
       {
         name: 'Overwrite Existing',
         value: 'overwrite',
       }
     ],
   }
   ```

2. List Fields
   ```typescript
   // Options list with descriptions
   {
     displayName: 'Operation',
     name: 'operation',
     type: 'options',
     options: [
       {
         name: 'Create',
         value: 'create',
         description: 'Create a new record',  // Optional description
       }
     ],
     default: 'create',  // Set most common option as default
   },

   // Multi-select list
   {
     displayName: 'Fields',
     name: 'fields',
     type: 'multiOptions',
     options: [
       {
         name: 'Email',
         value: 'email',
       }
     ],
     default: [],  // Empty array for multi-select
   }
   ```

3. ID Fields
   ```typescript
   // Support both list selection and direct ID input
   {
     displayName: 'Workspace Name or ID',
     name: 'workspaceId',
     type: 'string',
     hint: 'Choose from the list or specify an ID using an expression',
     default: '',
     description: 'The workspace to operate on',
     typeOptions: {
       loadOptionsMethod: 'getWorkspaces',
     },
   }
   ```

4. Date Fields
   ```typescript
   // Support all ISO 8601 formats
   {
     displayName: 'Due Date',
     name: 'dueDate',
     type: 'dateTime',
     default: '',
     description: 'Task due date (ISO 8601 format)',
     validateType: 'dateTime',
   }
   ```

5. Type Selection
   - Choose appropriate type for data
   - Consider user experience
   - Support multiple input methods
   - Provide clear validation

6. Default Values
   - Set sensible defaults
   - Document default behaviour
   - Handle empty values
   - Consider edge cases

7. Validation
   - Implement appropriate validation
   - Provide clear error messages
   - Handle edge cases
   - Support all formats

